				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Investor Activism, Already Robust, Expected to Rise in Next Year</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Michael J. de la Merced			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-10-29T14:01:06+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 29, 2014 10:01 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 29, 2014 10:01 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/29/investor-activism-already-robust-expected-to-rise-in-next-year/" data-title="Investor Activism, Already Robust, Expected to Rise in Next Year" data-description="A survey by the law firm Schulte Roth &amp; Zabel and the data provider Mergermarket, to be released on Wednesday, reflects the undiminished confidence in the power of outspoken dissident investors. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/30/business/dbpix-darden/dbpix-darden-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/30/business/dbpix-darden/dbpix-darden-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/30/business/dbpix-darden/dbpix-darden-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000003203477" width="480" height="371" alt="The activist hedge fund Starboard Value has pushed for changes at Darden Restaurants, the owner of Olive Garden."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="371"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The activist hedge fund Starboard Value has pushed for changes at Darden Restaurants, the owner of Olive Garden.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Steve Helber/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Activist shareholders have found significant success in shaking up corporate America in the last few years. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And virtually all the senior corporate executives and activist hedge fund managers <a href="//www.srz.com/files/upload/Publications/SRZ%202014_Shareholder_Activism_Insight_Report_HR.pdf">surveyed</a> by the law firm Schulte Roth &#038; Zabel and the data provider Mergermarket said they believed that activism would rise over the next 12 months. More than half said the increase would be âsubstantial.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The results, to be released at an activism conference hosted by Schulte Roth on Wednesday, signal the undiminished confidence in the power of outspoken dissident investors. Over the last year alone, activist shareholders have prompted management changes at Darden Restaurants, helped spur breakups at a slew of companies, and gained seats on numerous corporate boards.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Recent data suggests that the success of activism campaigns has more than doubled over the last decade, to more than 70 percent. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">With such a track record, perhaps it is no surprise that most of the survey respondents, including 98 percent in the United States, expect that level to rise in the coming year. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âSuccessful proxy contests lead to successful returns,â said David Rosewater, co-head of Schulte Rothâs activism practice. âThe biggest firms have brought it into the mainstream and made it more acceptable.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Aiding in that acceptance, he added, was the willingness of some of the biggest institutional investors to support activism campaigns, removing the stigma of backing an activist willing to wage war against management teams. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Activist investors are also more willing to broaden their suggestions beyond financial engineering moves like spinoffs or special dividends. Mr. Rosewater highlighted, for example, the nearly 300 pages of operational changes that Starboard Value suggested for Darden. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nearly half of respondents to the survey said calls for improved efficiency and resolving operational issues would underpin activist campaigns in the next year. The biggest drivers of campaigns, at least according to the survey, will remain companiesâ stock performance, changes to boards or management teams, and announced acquisitions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Optimism about the future of activism extended beyond American shores. Two-thirds of activist respondents said that they believed the investing strategy would pick up in Europe during the next 12 months. Why? One reason is that Europe offers a significant number of potential targets for campaigns, as a result of moribund national economies.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some of the campaigns in Europe will not be led by homegrown dissidents, but rather by big American investors flush with cash and eager to find new targets. Already, firms like Elliott Management and Sandell Asset Management have reportedly taken aim at European companies like the grocery chain Morrisons.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the increasing popularity of activism as a strategy ultimately weighs on profits. Just 20 percent of respondents to the Schulte Roth survey said they expected dissident campaigns to yield returns of 20 to 30 percent. Two years ago, 48 percent of respondents said those kinds of outsize returns were possible.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And 52 percent of activist respondents to the survey said they thought the increase in activist campaigns would lead to &#8220;overcrowding,&#8221; limiting the number of potential investment opportunities.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet Mr. Rosewater said he believed that activism would remain durable as an investment strategy, in large part because investors would always find room for improvement at companies.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âItâs hard to imagine that all of a sudden every company is perfectly managed and does things when they should,â he said.</p>
	</div>
